SCLCs were tested in electron-only devices configured with the ITO/ZnO/active layer/ZrAcac/Al and hole-only devices configured with the ITO/PEDOT:PSS/active layer/MoO3/Ag. The current density–voltage (J–V) characteristics of the hole or electron-only devices are fitted by the Mott–Gurney law:J=9/8εrε0μV2/L3,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$J = \left( {9/8} \right)\varepsilon _{\mathrm{r}}\varepsilon _0\mu \left( {V^2/{{L}}^3} \right),$$\end{document}where J is the current density, εr is the dielectric permittivity of the active layer, ε0 is the vacuum permittivity, L is the thickness of the active layer, μ is the mobility. V=Vapp−Vbi, where Vapp is the applied voltage and Vbi is the offset voltage (Vbi is 0 V here). The mobility can be calculated from the slope of the J0.5~V curves. Characteristic curves of SCLC devices are shown in Supplementary Fig. 48.
